# Red Hat AI — Inference Optimization Demo Suite

> Interactive demos explaining six LLM inference optimization techniques, built for engineers, practitioners, and anyone curious about how open-source AI infrastructure works.

**Live site:** `https://your-username.github.io/your-repo-name/`

---

## What This Is

A lightweight, zero-dependency web app that teaches LLM inference optimization through hands-on simulations. Each technique gets its own interactive demo — no slides, no walls of text. You learn by doing.

| Demo | Technique | Format |
|------|-----------|--------|
| 01 | Speculative Decoding | Live race simulation |
| 02 | Quantization + Compression | Pixel identification quiz |
| 03 | Sparsification | Neural network pruning sandbox |
| 04 | Prefill / Decode Disaggregation | Factory throughput simulation |
| 05 | Continuous Batching + Prefix Caching | Speed typing challenge |
| 06 | GuideLLM Benchmarking | *(coming soon)* |

All six techniques are upstream open-source projects that Red Hat actively contributes to or maintains.

---

## The Demos

### 01 · Speculative Decoding
A slowed-down (1000×) simulation of draft-model speculation. A small draft model races ahead to guess tokens; the large model verifies them all in one pass. You control draft speed, speculation window, and acceptance rate — and watch the speedup accumulate in real time.

**Why it matters:** 2–3× throughput improvement on code and structured-text workloads with zero change to output quality.

### 02 · Quantization + Compression
A six-question pixel art quiz. Images (Red Hat logo, Tux, Kubernetes wheel, etc.) are rendered at progressively lower bit depths — the same way model weights get compressed from FP32 to INT4. Guess what you're looking at. Your score reflects how much information you actually needed.

**Why it matters:** INT4 quantization reduces model memory by 87.5%, putting 70B models within reach of a single GPU.

### 03 · Sparsification
An interactive neural network pruner. Drag a sparsity slider from 0% to 95% and watch neurons go dark as the weakest weights get zeroed out. Live benchmark scores (MMLU, HumanEval, GSM8K) update in real time showing how well accuracy holds.

**Why it matters:** 50% sparse models can run at near-identical accuracy with 2× hardware throughput on NVIDIA Ampere/Hopper GPUs.

### 04 · Prefill / Decode Disaggregation
A factory simulation with two modes. In **Combined** mode, one GPU alternates between reading prompts and writing responses, starving itself. In **Disaggregated** mode, dedicated Prefill and Decode GPUs each run at full utilization. Watch TTFT and throughput diverge.

**Why it matters:** P/D disaggregation reduces Time to First Token by 2–4× for long prompts and improves overall cluster utilization.

### 05 · Continuous Batching + Prefix Caching
A speed-typing challenge with six prompts per round drawn from a randomized pool. Some prompts share prefixes with ones you've already typed — when you hit a cache match, the shared part is pre-filled and you only type the new suffix. After each round you can play again with the same prefix cache or clear it for a cold start.

**Why it matters:** Cache hit rates above 80% are common in production chatbot and RAG workloads, delivering 10–20× effective throughput gains.

---

## Upstream Projects

| Project | Role | Maintainer |
|---------|------|------------|
| [vLLM](https://github.com/vllm-project/vllm) | Primary serving engine; speculative decoding, prefix caching, PagedAttention | Community (Red Hat contributor) |
| [llm-compressor](https://github.com/vllm-project/llm-compressor) | Quantization + sparsification toolkit | Red Hat / Neural Magic |
| [SparseML](https://github.com/neuralmagic/sparseml) | Sparsification and pruning framework | Red Hat / Neural Magic |
| [LMCache](https://github.com/LMCache/LMCache) | Distributed KV cache sharing for P/D disaggregation | Community (Red Hat contributor) |
| [SGLang](https://github.com/sgl-project/sglang) | High-performance serving with RadixAttention | Community |
| [llama.cpp](https://github.com/ggml-org/llama.cpp) | CPU/edge inference with speculative decoding | Community |
| [GuideLLM](https://github.com/neuralmagic/guidellm) | Benchmarking and evaluation framework | Red Hat / Neural Magic |
| [Hugging Face TGI](https://github.com/huggingface/text-generation-inference) | Text generation inference server | Hugging Face |

